:"circa 1314","1342":"1342","1370":"1370","Drayton, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Drayton, Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Drayton, Hampshire, England":"Drayton, Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1314–":"about 1314–Deceased","1312–1342":"1312–1342","1338–1370":"1338–1370","1314–Female":"1314–Deceased","1338":"1338","1314":"1314","1312":"1312","about 1314":"about 1314","1342":"1342","1370":"1370","Drayton, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Drayton, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","Drayton, Hampshire, England":"Drayton, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form of a French or Flemish surname such as <b>Beaujean</b> and <b>Bejean</b>, from Old French <i>bel Jehan</i> ‘handsome John’ + excrescent <i>-t</i>. It could have been introduced to England in the 15th or 16th century by Flemish migrants."]},{"name":"Beacham","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Campbell","meanings":["Scottish: nickname from Gaelic <i>cam</i> ‘crooked, bent’ + <i>beul</i> ‘mouth’. As a result of folk etymology, the surname was often represented in Latin documents as <i>de bello campo</i> ‘of the fair field’, which led to the name sometimes being ‘translated’ into Anglo-Norman French as   Beauchamp  .","Irish (North Armagh): adopted for Gaelic <b>Mac Cathmhaoil</b> ‘son of Cathmhaol’ (literally ‘battle chief’): see   Caulfield   and   Cowell  .","English: variant of   Camel  , under the influence of the Scottish name (see 1 above)."]},{"name":"Bushaw","meanings":["Americanized form of French   Beauchamp   and   Bouchard  ."]},{"name":"Beacom","meanings":["English (Somerset) and Irish (Fermanagh): of Norman origin, a variant of   Beauchamp  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of any of the given names beginning with the letter <i>D-</i> (  compare  Jay   and   Kay  ), in particular   Dorothy .  It is also used as an independent name, and may in some cases be associated with the River Dee (  compare  Clyde  )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice de Beauchamp was born about 1314, in Drayton, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 daughter with Ralph De Arderne."},"et":{"about 1314–":"umbes 1314–Surnud","1312–1342":"1312–1342","1338–1370":"1338–1370","1314–Female":"1314–Surnud","1338":"1338","1314":"1314","1312":"1312","about 1314":"umbes 1314","1342":"1342","1370":"1370","Drayton, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Drayton, Worcestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Drayton, Hampshire, England":"Drayton, Hampshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1314–":"noin 1314–Kuollut","1312–1342":"1312–1342","1338–1370":"1338–1370","1314–Female":"1314–Kuollut","1338":"1338","1314":"1314","1312":"1312","about 1314":"noin 1314","1342":"1342","1370":"1370","Drayton, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Drayton, Worcestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Drayton, Hampshire, England":"Drayton, Hampshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1314–":"environ 1314–Décédée","1312–1342":"1312–1342","1338–1370":"1338–1370","1314–Female":"1314–Décédée","1338":"1338","1314":"1314","1312":"1312","about 1314":"environ 1314","1342":"1342","1370":"1370","Drayton, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Drayton, Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Drayton, Hampshire, England":"Drayton, Hampshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Alice de Beauchamp est née environ 1314, à Drayton, Worcestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Ralph De Arderne."},"de":{"about 1314–":"um 1314–Verstorben","1312–1342":"1